- Attachment is the operating system underneath every important relationship
    - Attachment theory comes from Bowlby and Ainsworth: humans evolved to seek and maintain proximity to a few specific caregivers
    - The attachment system runs on its own — it activates when threat or distance is sensed and seeks reassurance through closeness
    - It is not the same as love or compatibility; it is the body-level felt sense of "is this person available, present, and responsive to me?"
    - Adults have attachment systems too; they don't go away after childhood — they get reorganized and remapped onto romantic partners and a small handful of close others
    - The first relationships set the template; later relationships can revise it but only by sustained corrective experience
    - The whole book is a translation: how does this apply when you have multiple romantic partners?

- Secure attachment: the felt sense of "I matter to you, and I can rely on you"
    - In childhood, secure attachment forms when caregivers are consistently available, attuned, and responsive
    - The child learns: my needs are real, my distress will be met, the world is reasonable, I can return to my caregiver and also venture out
    - In adulthood, securely attached people can self-soothe AND turn to others; they don't have to choose
    - Secure adults expect responsiveness, ask for what they need, recover from rupture, and don't read every absence as abandonment
    - The body in secure attachment: regulated nervous system, easy reach for connection, easy retreat into solitude, neither activity is anxious
    - Earned secure attachment is real: through therapy, sustained good relationships, or deliberate work, an originally insecure person can develop secure functioning

- The insecure attachment styles
    - Anxious / preoccupied: the system is on high alert; absence feels like threat
        - Childhood pattern: caregiver was inconsistent — sometimes warm, sometimes unavailable — so the child learned to amplify protest to get attention
        - Adult pattern: hyper-vigilance to distance signals; reads small cues as rejection; protests, clings, escalates
        - The felt sense: "if I stop watching, I will be left"
        - Strengths: can be deeply loving, attuned to others' moods, motivated to repair
        - Costs: exhaustion, partner reads the protest as smothering, the watching itself prevents the closeness it seeks
    - Avoidant / dismissive: the system is shut down; closeness feels like threat
        - Childhood pattern: caregiver was reliably unavailable or rejecting — so the child learned to deactivate the attachment system entirely
        - Adult pattern: discomfort with vulnerability, retreat under stress, "I don't need anyone"
        - The felt sense: "closeness costs more than it gives"
        - Strengths: capable, self-reliant, can hold space alone
        - Costs: partner experiences a wall, intimacy stalls, the system never gets the corrective experience it needs to update
    - Disorganized / fearful-avoidant: the system is in conflict; closeness is both wanted and dangerous
        - Childhood pattern: caregiver was the source of fear (abuse, severe inconsistency, frightening behavior) — the child needed proximity but proximity was unsafe
        - Adult pattern: pulls in then pushes away; can feel "I want you, get away from me" in the same hour
        - The felt sense: "I want this AND I expect to be hurt by it"
        - Often the result of trauma; often co-occurs with PTSD or complex trauma
        - The most painful style for the person and their partners; also the one most responsive to skilled, consistent care
    - A caveat to the styles
        - Styles are not types; they are tendencies under stress
        - You may be secure with some people and anxious with others
        - You may be avoidant in romance and secure in friendship
        - Many people show different styles across different ages, partners, and life conditions
        - The styles describe the body's strategy under threat; they are not personality

- The nested model of attachment and trauma
    - Attachment doesn't only happen between two people; it nests in larger systems
    - Four levels, each shaping the next
    - Level 1: the self
        - Your relationship with your own body, mind, and inner experience
        - Self-attunement: noticing what you actually feel before reacting
        - Self-regulation: bringing yourself back to baseline without requiring another person
        - The inner nurturer: the part of you that responds to your own distress with care
        - Without secure self-attachment, every external relationship carries an extra weight: it must regulate something the inside can't yet hold
    - Level 2: family of origin and primary caregivers
        - The earliest template for what closeness costs and provides
        - This is what most attachment theory has historically focused on
        - It sets the implicit rules: who is available, who can be trusted, what happens when I express need
    - Level 3: community
        - Friends, extended family, neighborhoods, congregations, workplaces, scenes
        - Community-level secure attachment: a sense of belonging beyond any one relationship
        - Without community, even a strong primary relationship carries every social need; this overburdens the relationship
        - Insecure community shows up as isolation, scapegoating, "us vs them" patterns
    - Level 4: culture and society
        - The macro-level water you swim in: economic precarity, racism, queerphobia, ableism, colonization, religious oppression
        - These conditions can produce chronic threat that the nervous system has nowhere to discharge
        - Trauma at this level affects bodies even when the person is not the direct target — generational, witnessed, ambient
        - You can be doing all the right things at levels 1–3 and still carry a load that no individual relationship can resolve
    - The implication: working on attachment means working at all four levels, not just the dyad
        - Self-work, family-of-origin work, community-building, and resisting harmful systemic conditions are all attachment work
        - Insecurity at one level can be partially compensated by security at another, but only partially
    - Trauma layered on attachment
        - Shock trauma: a discrete event (assault, accident, sudden loss)
        - Developmental trauma: chronic mismatch over time, accumulating weight (chronic neglect, ongoing emotional unavailability)
        - Both shape the attachment system, but developmental trauma is harder to see because it doesn't have a single event to point to
        - The body keeps the score: trauma lives in the nervous system, not just memory; it gets re-triggered by similar relational signals

- Consensual nonmonogamy: the structures
    - Polyamory: multiple romantic and/or sexual relationships, all parties knowing and consenting
    - Open relationships: a primary couple plus separate sexual partners; rules vary
    - Relationship anarchy: refusing the assumption that romantic relationships should be ranked above other relationships
    - Swinging, kitchen-table polyamory, parallel polyamory, hierarchical vs egalitarian — many shapes
    - Common thread: explicit, ongoing consent; transparency; multiple emotionally significant connections
    - The book is not advocating any one structure; it is asking how the chosen structure interacts with attachment

- Why nonmonogamy can stress attachment
    - Attachment evolved with a small, stable circle in mind; multiple romantic attachments add load
    - Time and presence are finite; multiple partners means less of each per partner
    - The conditions of nonmonogamy can mimic the conditions of attachment insecurity
        - Inconsistency: when partners are out with other people, returning home is sometimes warm and sometimes preoccupied
        - Ambiguity: roles and expectations are less scripted than in monogamous defaults
        - Comparison: jealousy is a body signal that the attachment system has detected possible loss
    - This is not a verdict against nonmonogamy; it is a mapping of where the attachment system is likely to fire
    - The remedy is not to suppress the firing but to address what the body is actually signaling

- The HEARTS framework: how to be polysecure with partners
    - The acronym names six moves that build attachment-based security in a relationship
    - Each is asked in two directions: how do you offer this to your partner, and how do you receive it from them?
    - Each chapter has reflection questions to ground the move in your specific relationship
    - H: Here, with each partner
        - Be physically and emotionally present when you are with each partner; reduce the distractions, the half-attention, the parallel-tasking
        - Presence is the felt sense that "you are with me, not somewhere else"
        - In nonmonogamy: when you return from another partner, fully arrive — don't leave half of yourself there
        - Availability and responsiveness are downstream of presence; you can't be available when you are absent
    - E: Expressed delight
        - Show your partner that they are unique, special, and precious to you — by what you say, what you do, how you look at them
        - This is a counter-move to the way nonmonogamy can feel like commodification (one of many)
        - Specific, particular delight: the things you love about THIS person, not generic affirmation
        - In nonmonogamy: expressed delight is often what partners need most before or after another partner's date — to know they remain irreplaceable to you, not interchangeable
    - A: Attunement
        - Track your partner's inner experience; notice when they shift; check in with what is happening underneath
        - Attunement is the difference between "I see you" and "I see what you presented"
        - It requires slowing down, asking, and listening
        - In nonmonogamy: attunement to how each partner is doing in the configuration is non-optional — generic check-ins miss the actual state
        - The skill to develop: noticing your partner's distress before they have to escalate to get you to notice
    - R: Rituals and routines
        - Predictable, repeated practices that signal "we are together" — daily check-ins, weekly dates, anniversary practices, going-and-returning rituals
        - Rituals create attachment safety because they make the relationship visible and reliable to the nervous system
        - In nonmonogamy: rituals around departures and arrivals are particularly important — what do you do before a date with another partner? what do you do when you come back?
        - These don't have to be elaborate; they have to be consistent
    - T: Turning toward after conflict
        - Repair after rupture is the single biggest predictor of long-term relational health
        - The pattern: rupture happens (it always does) → notice → turn back → acknowledge impact → take responsibility → reconnect
        - Avoiding repair lets ruptures accumulate; the relationship feels increasingly distant even when no single event seems decisive
        - In nonmonogamy: jealousy events, schedule conflicts, and asymmetric news (one partner has new news, the other doesn't) all need active repair
        - Repair is not a single technique; it is the willingness to come back
    - S: Secure attachment with self
        - Without self-security, no amount of partner-work fully lands; the partner cannot fix what only the self can do
        - The four sub-moves of self-security mirror the HEART moves applied internally
        - This is the largest single section of the book and gets its own chapter

- Secure attachment with self: HEARTS turned inward
    - Be Here with yourself
        - Notice what your body is doing right now; what your nervous system is feeling
        - Most people avoid being present with themselves through busyness, scrolling, substances, or other people
        - Practices: somatic noticing, meditation, walking without input, sitting still
        - The capacity to be alone with yourself without crisis is the foundation of secure functioning
    - Self-expressed delight
        - The way you talk to yourself; the value you assign your own experience
        - The opposite is the inner critic: the relentless voice that flags every shortcoming
        - Self-expressed delight is not narcissism; it is the basic respect that you would extend to a friend
        - Practice: catch the inner critic; ask "would I say this to someone I love?"; revise toward truth and care
    - Self-attunement and self-regulation
        - Self-attunement: knowing what you actually feel — not what you think you should feel, not what is convenient
        - Self-regulation: returning yourself to baseline without requiring another to do it for you
        - Auto-regulation through others: the pattern of needing partner / phone / substance to soothe instead of doing the work yourself
        - The inner nurturer: the part of you that meets your own distress with steadiness instead of judgment
        - Building self-attunement is slow somatic work; there is no shortcut
    - Self-rituals
        - Routines and practices that align you with the version of yourself you are trying to be
        - Morning practices, sleep practices, body practices, contemplative practices
        - These create internal continuity; they tell your nervous system "the world has reliable structure, even when relationships shift"
        - In nonmonogamy: solid self-rituals are protection — when partner-time fluctuates, your own scaffolding holds
    - Turning toward yourself after rupture
        - When you let yourself down, the work of self-repair: notice, acknowledge, take responsibility without crushing yourself, recommit
        - The rupture-and-repair cycle applies internally too
        - Self-compassion in the Kristin Neff sense: common humanity ("everyone fails sometimes"), mindfulness ("here is what is happening"), kindness ("I will treat myself with care")

- The foundations beneath the HEARTS
    - Commitment: do you and your partner want to be attachment figures for each other?
        - Not all relationships should be attachment-based; some should remain casual, friendly, sexual without the attachment work
        - Naming the type of relationship reduces ambiguity and prevents the partner who wants attachment from over-investing
        - Reflection question to discuss with each potentially-attachment partner: what does commitment mean to you? what level of involvement and availability do we want with each other?
    - Safe haven: is this person someone I can come to when I am hurting?
        - The safe haven is the side of attachment that meets distress
        - It is the partner who can hold your hard moments without flinching, without rushing to fix, without making it about them
        - The reflection question: how does this partner already act as a safe haven for me? How can I be more of one for them?
    - Secure base: is this person someone who supports me venturing out?
        - The secure base is the side of attachment that supports growth and exploration
        - It is the partner who cheers your projects, your other relationships, your becoming
        - The reflection question: how does this partner support my growth? How could I better support theirs?
    - In nonmonogamy: different partners can offer more safe-haven or more secure-base roles
        - The benefit of multiple relationships is that no single person has to be everything
        - The risk is fragmentation if no one is offering secure-base or safe-haven adequately

- Boundaries: the membrane of secure functioning
    - Boundaries are not walls; they are the membrane that allows what nourishes and blocks what harms
    - Two failure modes
        - Porous: too little protection — absorbing others' emotions, taking on responsibility that isn't yours, intrusive (taking up too much of others' space)
        - Rigid: too much blocking — refusing connection, walling off vulnerability, restraining (cutting off your own expression)
    - Healthy boundaries are responsive: they tighten where damage is happening, soften where connection is wanted
    - Four boundary failures
        - Over-giving: providing more than is sustainable, often from a belief that your value depends on it
        - Under-giving: withholding what you could offer, often from fear of losing yourself
        - Over-receiving / over-taking: pulling more from others than is fair, often from a sense of scarcity
        - Under-receiving: refusing to let in what's offered, often from rigidity or distrust
    - In nonmonogamy: boundaries become more complex because more people are in the system
        - What information do you share with which partner about other partners?
        - What time and energy commitments are appropriate for each connection?
        - What kinds of emotional labor are reasonable to expect from each partner?
    - The reflection questions help locate where your particular pattern lives
        - Where do you over-give? Where do you under-give?
        - Where are your boundaries porous? Where are they rigid?
        - What needs tightening? What needs softening?

- Common challenges and final thoughts
    - Jealousy is information, not a verdict
        - Jealousy is a body signal that the attachment system has detected possible loss or displacement
        - It does not mean the relationship is wrong, the partner is doing something wrong, or you are bad
        - The work: feel the signal, locate what it is pointing to, address that underlying need
        - Sometimes jealousy points to a real attunement gap; sometimes to a self-security gap; sometimes to an unprocessed history
    - Compersion is real but not mandatory
        - Compersion: the experience of joy at a partner's connection with someone else
        - Some people feel it readily; others develop it; some never reliably feel it and that is also okay
        - The pressure to feel compersion can become its own form of self-betrayal
    - Configurations change over time
        - Attachment-based relationships can become friendships; casual connections can become attachment-based
        - The work is to keep the configuration honest and consensual as it evolves
        - "Polyamory is a practice, not an identity" — what was true last year may not be true now
    - There is no formula
        - The HEARTS framework is a map, not a recipe
        - Every relationship and every configuration requires its own ongoing translation
        - The work is to keep the body, the heart, and the structure aligned — and to repair when they drift out of alignment
